Linked Lists:

-> Unlike arrays , Linkedlists dont store elements in contiguos memory locations.
-> Linkedlist is a linear data structure where nodes are connected using pointers

Dynamic in size : Can grow or shrink in size at runtime without reallocating memory like arrays.
Efficient insertion or deletion
Sequential access :You must traverse from the start to reach a particular node (no direct indexing like arrays).	



REAL WORLD EXAMPLES:
Real-World Example: Music Player
Imagine you’re listening to songs in a playlist:

Each song is a node.

The playlist is a doubly linked list:

Each node has a pointer to the next song and the previous song.

When you hit Next, you follow the next pointer.

When you hit Previous, you follow the prev pointer.

This way, you can move back and forth seamlessly without needing to know the index of the song (like you would in an array).

🌐 Web Browser Navigation
Browsers use a doubly linked list to manage history.

Each page visited is a node:

next → the page you go forward to.

prev → the page you came from.

Clicking Back or Forward is just following these pointers.

